segments.text: But what I'm trying to do is put together a little history of the executive secretary's position with the Texas Medical Association.
I'll have to ramble a little bit.
In fact, I'll have to go back and refer to some of my notes on dates.
But for specific dates, times, and places, we'll have to refer to the Texas Federal Bulletin, which is on file in the Austin office.
We will start with the year 1943.
Many, many things happened during that particular year.
And if you may recall, it was the tail end of the war period.
Dr. T.O.
Booth was state veterinarian in the early part of 42, and volunteered to go back into the service.
Dr. M.B.
Stearns of Dallas was the original editor of the Texas Veterinary Bulletin and had issued some two or three issues prior to his return to military service.
And I think if we check the bulletin records, we'll find that Dr. Booth probably published at least one or two.
But I became a state veterinarian upon the volunteering of Dr. T.O.
Booth.
I was assistant state veterinarian at the time, stationed in New Brunswick, Texas.
When a group of my colleagues got together in Austin and decided that I should move on up as state veterinarian,
It was a rather embarrassing situation because, first off, they had agreed to assess veterinarians in Texas to supplement the paycheck for state veterinarians.
Believe it or not, in 1943, the state veterinarian's salary was $2,750 a year, plus expenses.
decided to go to Fort Worth, become the state veterinarian, but the course could not accept any contributions from my colleagues.
As it turned out, I inherited the Texas Veterinarian Billetton and also the secretaryship of the State Veterinary Medical Association, or the Texas Veterinary Medical Association.
We were able to
maneuver and manage I officed in the W.T.

Wagner building downtown Fort Worth and there was a small office on the same floor available and I rented that office and placed the secretary and the bulletin office in that room the idea being that I did not want to be
in a position of conflict of interest, and by separating the offices, we at least could show our desire to remain a separate entity.
Again, during that year, I also inherited a position on the World Manpower Commission
which had to do with the drafting of veterinarians or also drafting of all professional people such as physicians, nurses, dentists, and the like.
Mine was representing the veterinary profession.
So 1943 was a bang-up start for the first time probably in the history.
was a separate and complete office for the Executive Secretary of the Texas Veteran Association.
I mentioned the War Mountain Fire Commission, the Bulletin, and so forth, all supplemented towards this office.
And the expenses alone were all that were taken by me as

secretary at the time and this was a brand new step because the first time any funds had been provided to a secretary per se the title of executive secretary just kind of grew out of the position we managed to get some furniture from the wall mine power commission which was a government agency desk chairs the like cabinet filing cabinets
I began to step out, and then, of course, the first major step was to gather funds to continue the publication of the Texas Veterinarian Bill.
This put us into the advertising game, and, of course, we catered to advertisers with sales only to veterinarians.
We were rather selfish and aristocratic in our procedures because we set a fee for the advertising that was necessary to cover the cost of the publication.
And many of the companies we dealt with had advertising agencies who had always expected a commission.
We had a flat rate and told them so.
Of course, they felt like they were obligated, in a sense, to advertise with us, so we got along beautifully in that route.

The reason I rival so much here is that for the ten years that I served as the Executive Secretary, 95 percent of its success could be based upon the fact that it was a veterinarian representing veterinarians.
and the various positions that I held during that interim complemented or assisted in our development.

In so many words, we could not have grown as rapidly as I think we did had it not been for the fact that as state veterinarian I was able to work it right along hand in hand in my visitations out over the state and the like, created the atmosphere of
consultation, etc.
The year 1943 was a definite growing up period of the Texas Veterinary Medical Association.
I mention this because it was also a growing up period of the acceptance of the veterinary profession, the pressures that were placed upon them during the war period,
The fact that unless they were essentially classified within their area or territory, they were vulnerable to the draft.
All in all, it was a tremendous transition.
I'll have to, of course, compare the various positions that I held during that time as having direct influence and vice versa on each other.
The state veterinarian's office was largely managed and handled by a layperson who was called a director.

And there was a constant maneuver that took place between he and I during that period, resulting finally in the reestablishment of the state veterinarian as the director and the administrative office of the Livestock Sanitary Commission of Texas.
It was an uphill battle because, again, we were feeling our way by interrelationship between the veterinary profession and the enforcement agencies, as was the state veterinary.
The enforcement, of course, necessitated a closer relationship because, in many instances, there was a pot called the kettle black, and the veterinarian in the field was actually responsible
for carrying out the majority of the enforcement regulations of that department.
Thus, a constant source of information could be sent out by way of the Texas Veteran Air Bulletin with the interlocking of the duties of the two offices.
I know this is rambling and it's hard to explain,
We did begin to understand the requirements necessary for veterinarians to make interstate shipments and handle livestock disease outbreaks and on and on and on.
We felt kind of lonesome during that period insofar as communications between veterinarians back to their alma mater at A&M

uh all of these uh it looked like the veterinarian was the last one to receive any information and the rest of it went out to the agricultural channels to the county agents and so this led on then eventually to the movement of the office finally to a m

at which time in 1945 I accepted the position of Extension Veteran, again taking the office of the State Association with me, with the full sanction of my bosses and the like, and we established another office, what was called the North Gate of Texas A&M.
It was an upstairs office, again keeping our relationships separated as much as possible.
When we got into the extension veterinary side of it, it was with the full understanding of the bosses that we were going into an educational period.
The prime purpose of my employment was to cement relationships
between the various agricultural representatives, such as county agents, and the local veterinarian.
Kind of a goodwill emissary, and at the same time offered the golden opportunity to visit with all of the veterinarians in Texas.
In fact, Dr. Marsteller, my previous dean of the veterinary school, was very envious of the fact that I couldn't go out all over Texas.
Also, it was true of the faculty of the veterinary college.
I was free to travel the state of Texas, preach the gospel, but I tried desperately to come back and at least report to the dean of the veterinary school of what was happening out there.
The Texas Gun Air Bill continued.
Each time, as in Fort Worth and also at A&M, it was printed and handled by local printing companies and was absolutely free of any other connection.
The period of 43 to 45
I mentioned was a growing up period.
We took veterinarians from cowboy boots to tuxedos.
We had many meetings, you know, as it was established, one in the summer at A&M and one in the fall elsewhere through the state.
These were largely fraternal-type meetings.
We did have good programs.
But the camaraderie and so forth began to build a profession to recognize each other's talents and abilities and began to work together.
The most outstanding meeting, I guess, during that particular period

I don't remember the exact date without checking, but it was a combination meeting of the Southern Veterinary Medical Association held in Dallas, Texas, when Dr. R.A. Self of Dallas was the local chairman, and we had a rather large gathering of veterinarians from Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama, et cetera.
So much for that, Rodman, and the period of A&M episode.
She made the relationships a great deal between the veterinary school and the veterinary profession because we were on the same ground and territories.
And it had grown and developed so much that
By that time, they were paying a fixed salary and offering secretarial assistance to the executive secretary.
This is where the program began to grow.
In 1948, I accepted a position of pharmaceutical representative for one of the solid veterinary supply houses

United States and it was done I know because of my contact throughout the state and they bought that rather than any particular ability again I was free to wander the state of Texas under the guise of

service representing the veterinary supply house but always been able to carry on the duties and responsibilities of the executive secretary and build the bulletin into a much better publication and also carry the gospel to the veterinarians of texas

about that time of course in between there we lost the dean of the veterinary school started searching for new ones wound up with dr rc dunn as acting dean and we began to try hard to put together the extension veterinary directly into the veterinary school this was a hopefully an act that would be accepted at that time but it wasn't and of course that
again, disturbed me enough to move on to the next step.
From the latter part of 1949, I got the desire to come back home and get back into general practice.
Having done all of these other things over a period of many years, I was beginning to feel like it was time to settle down.
So I came back to New Braunfels at the request of a cooperative group and organized a co-op cremary.
I built it from scratch and managed it through to 1951.
And during the time of the co-op cremary, I established my own veterinary hospital.
Dan was able to put my office or the executive secretary's office all into one unit.
I had a full-time secretary to assist and an awful good local printing publisher that assisted us in maintaining and keeping the bulletin going.
And the only difficulty arose, of course, was still some callbacks on other relationships we'd had over a period of time.
In other words, it wound up or accumulated or cumulated or whatever the word I want to use.
In 1953, thereabouts, they had a landfrax outbreak in Wichita Falls.
At the request of a colleague in Wichita, I was called up to assist in negotiating some kind of a diplomatic maneuver.
The Red Hands were all feeling a sudden burst of popularity, and each one feeling like he was a hotshot for the area.
The livestock side of the commission was balking.

The local cattle raisers were squawking, and so I reluctantly went up, visited with the practitioners for breakfast, settled on one representative, made our pitch to the cattlemen, and then was turned down by the livestock signer commission, and I began to realize that
In my position, I was no longer speaking for the profession.
It was kind of a lonesome affair and felt like it was time to move on.
So in 1953, I resigned as executive secretary and was awarded a lifetime membership in the Texas Dynamical Association.
So far, this sounds like
purely a personal history.
And therefore, this segment, we will attempt to cover some of the accomplishments that we feel like took place during those 10 years in the veterinary profession itself.
First off, we'll go back and repeat that the association to the various offices held
and the fact that I was a veterinarian I think helped tremendously in that period of ten years.
We were talking to each other, we were understanding each other, and the association began to grow.
The early years were largely

expenses were taken care of by a registration fee at the conventions these were nominal and largely paid just for the convention there was no surplus funds developed at that time as we began to grow of course developed the commercial aspect of displays
and began to make a little bit of money off the convention to assist in the growth of the office.
Some of the major highlights, I think, probably took place in the changeover in the state veterinarian's office, put the veterinarian back into his position of responsibility.
This was all done by full knowledge of the profession itself,
of what was taking place and what was going on.
Also, we began to diligently participate in disease outbreaks of all types with tremendous cooperation from A&M Experiment Station.
We began to get first-hand information on what was going on and were able to transmit it back to the veterinary profession
rally the troops, as the words are, and begin to intelligently approach such things as rabies outbreaks and the like.
Many, many experiences directly with local veterinary associations were necessary during that particular time.
This, of course, expanded greatly during the extension period at A&M because of the relationship
ability to take a faculty member or a experiment station member directly with you in contact with the general public and the veterinary detectives.
I also recall that the sessions of the Veterinary Association were held in the summer and the fall.
In the fall elsewhere over the state, in the summer always at A&M.
We've managed to encourage A&M
to understand that we were a profession such as anything that came out of the college, from engineer or whatnot.
And we felt like they owed an obligation to the profession just like they did to those others.
And they were holding various
type summer seminars for other groups, and so during that period they did agree and took over the summer session as a college-sponsored event.
The conventions that were held, like I mentioned before, were largely fraternal type.
Everybody had a good time, lots of entertaining and visitations and bill sessions.
But began to develop a strong program covering the general practice of MMS.
The specialization began to appear and the use of radiological equipment and on and on and on.
All of those developments were

In other words, the veterinary executive secretary was closely related to that development program and consequently kept it within the realm of what they felt was actually the needs of the profession at the time.
I guess the big highlight was the fact that we changed from enforcement aspects or studies to educational.
And in the educational realm, we just had a case recently to recall that 40-some odd years ago we organized the first
group of interested cattlemen in brucellosis.
We had representatives of sheep, goat, and raisers, the swine breeders, the herford breeders, the shorthorn breeders, the Texas Cattle Raisers Association, and on and on.
And we were able to put together a session at NM, which

We thought we had full agreement of all of the representatives of the various breed organizations, but were flat overruled on parliamentary procedure by the Texas Cattle Raiders Association, in which they said that those people all had to go back to their organizations, get their approval before they could vote.
on any program for the state of Texas.
Ironically, here it is 40-some-odd years later.
They had a big wrestle in the legislature this last session.
Someday, someday.
The rest of it, I'll have to refer to the Texas Department of Buildings because it attempted
during that period to pretty much carry the minutes of the various meetings held by the organization.
The board of directors, the executive board, all functioned in proper procedures and orders, and nearly all of the work was carried out.
specifically based upon the desires of the representatives of the veteran profession.
There were no new innovative programs that I can think of at the moment that were revolutionary, but just a steady, progressive development of the profession itself.
This is another form of reminiscing over a period of, well, I guess you'd call it veterinary medicine in general.
Dr. Bob Norton's here now and raised a few questions about Dr. Mark Francis and Dr. Hubert Schmidt and Dr. Marsteller and some of those in the heydays.
Actually, Dr. Francis was the first major participant in the organization of the Texas Veterinarians.
He was also licensed number one in the state of Texas.
Dr. Marsteller was his protege, and so was Dr. Hubert Schmidt.
Hubert came to A&M from Comfort, Texas.
As an agriculture student and befriended Dr. Francis, Francis encouraged him to go back to Berlin, Germany, and he did.
He got his degree there and came back and worked the rest of his life bringing him in.
Dr. Marsteller was a friend from Ohio that Dr. Francis brought down early in the organization or early beginning of Edmure School.
Dr. Francis came originally in the agricultural

aspects of it did a little work in the early experiment days and also is responsible for dr rc dunn who came in and actually built a laboratory and produced the whole collar vaccine on the campus i think now it's a veterinary museum or it was for a while i don't know what the building is now i think they moved some of that to the new library the uh
Dr. Francis was an old philosopher, really, as a teacher.
He used to act out a number of things.
I never will forget when he was giving us a description of the upper esophagus and its relationship with the trachea and so forth.
He described it as an old bill downtown on a Saturday afternoon buying a red soda water
And when he drank it, you'd see that old atom dropper jump up and down, and then he'd give a description of how it's all interconnected and those type illustrations.
He was not truly a teacher in the sense that he didn't conform with college rules or regulations.
All of our examinations were pick out five students in the room and have them write five questions on the boards.
We'd answer all the questions.
We were not permitted to leave the room until the last man finished.
And he'd take all the papers and throw them in a trash can and said, the college said I had to give you a test, but they didn't say a word about who was to grade the papers.
He did all of his grading based on attendance in his classroom and his observation of your procedures and your attitudes and the like.
I had him, fortunately, for both years of anatomy and, of course, in the latter two
We were only associated with them on a friendship basis through Dr. Dunn's sister-in-law, Evelyn Cahill, who was Dr. Francis and Dr. Marsteller's secretary.
So was Mary Dunn, who was Dr. Dunn's wife, who was also a secretary in the veterinary school.
Dr. Francis' main family family, I guess, came, of course, with his sister.
dipping of cattle for the Texas Fever State.
But his other was association with an old gentleman over in the biology department.
I can't think of his name right now, but biology and botany.
And they used to go together every Saturday down in the Brazos River bottoms on archaeological projects.
